s=\"d-lg-none d-flex zDocsFeedbackButton\" data-backdrop=\"static\" data-return-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2530992\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Dez 19, 2025</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104poh1665702907223.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/poh1665702907223.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/poh1665702907223.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"poh1665702907223\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Implementing a Client/Server Security Driver\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body taskbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">You can implement a custom client/server security driver using the Security Driver API.\n </p>\n<section class=\"section context\" id=\"poh1665702907223__context_w5128ab1b5b1_w5129ab1b5_w5130ab1\">\n<div class=\"div context\" id=\"poh1665702907223__topic_d40313e1_d40314e1_d40315e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40316e1_d40317e1_d40318e1\">The security driver provided by Uniface supports encoded connect messages and message header data using Base64 encoding and decoding algorithms. It can be used as is, but you may want to create your own driver to meet your specific environment and needs.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table class=\"table\" count-columns=\"2\" id=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1\"><caption><span class=\"table--title-label\">Table 1. </span><span class=\"title\">Client/Server Security Driver Files</span></caption><colgroup><col/><col/></colgroup><thead class=\"thead\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<th class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" id=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__1\">\n Source File\n </th>\n<th class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" id=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__2\">\n Description\n </th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody class=\"tbody\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__1\">\n<span class=\"ph filepath\">zsecdrv.h</span>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__2\">\n Generic Security Driver API\n </td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__1\">\n<span class=\"ph filepath\">unienc.h</span>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__2\">\n Functions for common encryption algorithms, including Base64, DES, HMAC, MD4, and MD5. To make use of these, include the file <span class=\"ph filepath\">unienc.h</span>.\n </td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__1\">\n<span class=\"ph filepath\">zsecdrv.mk</span>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"poh1665702907223__table_d3938e1_d3939e1_d3940e1__entry__2\">\n C make file for building the security driver\n \n                        </td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40319e1_d40320e1_d40321e1\">Files are located in <span class=\"ph filepath\">\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">InstallDir</var>/uniface/3gl/include</span> unless otherwise indicated.</p>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"poh1665702907223__note_w5131ab1b5b1b1b9_w5132ab1b5b1b1_w5133ab1b5b1_w5134ab1b5_w5135ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> Compiled libraries for the drivers are provided in\n                  the<span class=\"ph filepath\">/common/bin</span>(Windows)\n               or<span class=\"ph filepath\">/common/lib</span>(Unix) directory of your Uniface installation. The\n               C source files for the security drivers provided by Uniface are available as a sample\n               on <a class=\"xref\" href=\"https://community.rocketsoftware.com/uniface-community-samples-91\" rel=\"external noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Rocket Community</a>.</div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40325e1_d40326e1_d40327e1\">You can write your own security driver in any language that supports creating a shared library or DLL. To implement and use a custom client/server security driver</p>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section><ol class=\"ol steps\"><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"poh1665702907223__li_d20168e1_d20169e1_d20170e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40328e1_d40329e1_d40330e1\">Include the definitions provided by the API\n                  (<span class=\"ph filepath\">zsecdrv.h</span> and <span class=\"ph filepath\">unienc.h</span>) in your source\n               file. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"aqt1665702677943.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/aqt1665702677943.html\" title=\"Uniface provides an API for creating custom client/server and SMTP and POP security drivers. The API include files for the C compiler and libraries are provided in the Uniface/3gl directory.\">APIs: Security Driver</a>. </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<p class=\"p\">For example, you can define a different name for the entry point, or implement a\n                  different encryption algorithm.</p>\n</div>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"poh1665702907223__li_d20171e1_d20172e1_d20173e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Compile the source into a standard shared library for your platform, where the entry point function is an exported function that may be called. Refer to one of the sample make files provided.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"poh1665702907223__li_d20174e1_d20175e1_d20176e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40331e1_d40332e1_d40333e1\">Enable the security driver by declaring the entry\n               point of the driver in the <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"daw1665702678607.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/daw1665702678607.html\" title=\"Use the [USER_3GL] section of the assignment file to lists third-party components and Uniface 3GL extensions to be made available to Uniface.\">[USER_3GL]</a> section of the\n               assignment files of all cooperating applications. If you are using other shared\n               libraries, declare those as well. </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<p class=\"p\">For example, for Microsoft Windows:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[USER_3GL]\nc:/uniface/bin/zsecdrv(usecappl)\n</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40334e1_d40335e1_d40336e1\">For Unix:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[USER_3GL]\n/uniface/lib/zsecdrv(usecappl)\n</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</div>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"poh1665702907223__li_d20177e1_d20178e1_d20179e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40337e1_d40338e1_d40339e1\">Optionally, enable the extended login\n               functionality by specifying the paths to which it should apply in the <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"fqw1665702740209.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fqw1665702740209.html\" title=\"Use the [XLOGIN] section in the client assignment file on Windows platform to specify network paths to a Sun Solaris server that requires extended login.\">[XLOGIN]</a> section. </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<p class=\"p\">All the network paths specified in the [XLOGIN] section of an application’s\n                  assignment file use the same security driver, if it is specified.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"poh1665702907223__p_d40340e1_d40341e1_d40342e1\">For example:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[PATHS]\n$TCP = tcp:myhost|myuser|mypassword|ASV\n$XYZ = ...\n...\n[XLOGIN]\nPATHS = TCP, XYZ\n</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</div>\n</li></ol></section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ktb1665702890698.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Support for 3GL Languages</a><p>Strictly speaking, the interface between Uniface and 3GL is not tied to any specific language. You should be able to use the language of your choice, as long as the certain conditions are met.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2530992\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2530992\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Implementing a Client/Server Security Driver Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Dez 19, 2025 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Implementing a Client/Server Security Driver You can implement a custom client/server security driver using the Security Driver API. The security driver provided by Uniface supports encoded connect messages and message header data using Base64 encoding and decoding algorithms. It can be used as is, but you may want to create your own driver to meet your specific environment and needs. Table 1. Client/Server Security Driver Files Source File Description zsecdrv.h Generic Security Driver API unienc.h Functions for common encryption algorithms, including Base64, DES, HMAC, MD4, and MD5. To make use of these, include the file unienc.h . zsecdrv.mk C make file for building the security driver Files are located in InstallDir /uniface/3gl/include unless otherwise indicated. Note: Compiled libraries for the drivers are provided in the /common/bin (Windows) or /common/lib (Unix) directory of your Uniface installation. The C source files for the security drivers provided by Uniface are available as a sample on Rocket Community . You can write your own security driver in any language that supports creating a shared library or DLL. To implement and use a custom client/server security driver Include the definitions provided by the API ( zsecdrv.h and unienc.h ) in your source file. For more information, see APIs: Security Driver . For example, you can define a different name for the entry point, or implement a different encryption algorithm. Compile the source into a standard shared library for your platform, where the entry point function is an exported function that may be called. Refer to one of the sample make files provided. Enable the security driver by declaring the entry point of the driver in the [USER_3GL] section of the assignment files of all cooperating applications. If you are using other shared libraries, declare those as well. For example, for Microsoft Windows: [USER_3GL] c:/uniface/bin/zsecdrv(usecappl) Copy For Unix: [USER_3GL] /uniface/lib/zsecdrv(usecappl) Copy Optionally, enable the extended login functionality by specifying the paths to which it should apply in the [XLOGIN] section. All the network paths specified in the [XLOGIN] section of an application’s assignment file use the same security driver, if it is specified. For example: [PATHS] $TCP = tcp:myhost|myuser|mypassword|ASV $XYZ = ... ... [XLOGIN] PATHS = TCP, XYZ Copy Related Links Support for 3GL Languages Strictly speaking, the interface between Uniface and 3GL is not tied to any specific language. You should be able to use the language of your choice, as long as the certain conditions are met. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}